## Qualitative Results

The qualitative comparison showed that in 3 out of 5 examples, the PPO model received a higher `nothate` reward than the reference model.

This means that, in several examples, the PPO-updated model generated responses that the reward model considered less toxic or more aligned with the `nothate` class.

Some examples still received lower rewards after PPO, which is expected because this was a lightweight educational experiment with only a few PPO steps.

----------------------------------------------------
## Key Learning

This lab showed how a reward model can guide an LLM toward safer outputs.

PPO uses reward signals to update the model policy, while the frozen reference model helps prevent the updated model from drifting too far from the original behavior.

PEFT/LoRA makes this process more efficient by training only a small percentage of the model parameters instead of updating the entire base model.

